arguable that a little bit on this

stunning samples on the entire record
land on this track too the whole thing
sounds like a movie the focus on this lp
shows up even further on sir douglas
mawson which puts us in the mindset of a
guy who is pretty much trapped in a
corner by what he creates the world what
he creates exists in his own behaviors
toward those around him systems of
oppression as well as his own voluntary
ignorance it's a strong statement but
one of a few tracks on this thing i wish
were structured out a bit more as the
fade out ending on this track feels a
bit inconclusive and the samples can
really only function in place of a
proper chorus on this record so many
times i think variation in song writing
and song structure really needed to be
accounted for especially as gaiu starts
to go the distance on the next few
tracks here mimicry of the settlers for
example does start to drone on after a
bit even if a lot of the lyrical content
being brought to the table is sharp and
respect to any song titled i personally
wouldn't have released john mccain there

moments of the lp though like the
chilling religious chants interspersed
between bars about trauma and fighting

their confinement and then we have the
really epic closer shirk and i will give
it to gaius it does end the record off
with a bang a really warm sample
kind of a ray of light in a way which
does make sense because this record has
been very dark and very bold and very
grim and very
material in terms of the ugly realities
that it's staring very boldly into for
much of its run time overall came away
from this record really impressed there
are a lot of very forward-thinking bops
on this thing guys comes through with a
lot of great bars strong verses strong
samples a ton of base level talent but
as far as like song writing and song
structuring and sound play go i think
that he's is still in a bit of an
